</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C24F36A3315F1E31FABACE0FE05F8432" blockId="11.[707,1194,991,1729]" box="[731,1059,1575,1596]" pageId="11">
<emphasis id="F084EAB1315F1E31FABACE0FE7B98432" bold="true" box="[731,965,1575,1596]" pageId="11">Temporal Distribution.</emphasis>
July (1).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="8AEA6528315F1E36FABACE6AE51A842C" lastPageId="12" pageId="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="C24F36A3315F1E36FABACE6AE53E82FC" blockId="11.[707,1194,991,1729]" lastBlockId="12.[151,639,194,1570]" lastPageId="12" pageId="11">
<emphasis id="F084EAB1315F1E31FABACE6AE7388459" bold="true" box="[731,836,1602,1623]" pageId="11">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The characters listed in the generic diagnosis, greatly reduced flight wings, the unique form of the parameres, and the occurrence in the 
<collectingRegion id="0034F841315F1E31FB22CEBAE78884A9" box="[835,1012,1682,1703]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="11">Galápagos Islands</collectingRegion>
will serve to distinguish this species. The only other New World dynastine with this form of parameres is 
<taxonomicName id="05F04D2031581E36FA4CC8EAE53E82FC" authority="Dupuis." authorityName="Dupuis." class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Tomarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rostratus">
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36FA4CC8EAE49782FC" italics="true" pageId="12">Tomarus rostratus</emphasis>
Dupuis.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C24F36A331581E36F8CEC8DFE640815B" blockId="12.[151,639,194,1570]" pageId="12">
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36F8CEC8DFE52E8302" bold="true" box="[175,338,247,268]" pageId="12">Natural History.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="1D4B880131581E36F9E3C8DFE5A88302" box="[386,468,247,268]" pageId="12">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName id="05F04D2031581E36F993C8DFE6028302" authorityName="Ratcliffe" authorityYear="2014" box="[498,638,247,268]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Adelaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretus">
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36F993C8DFE6028302" box="[498,638,247,268]" italics="true" pageId="12">A. anachoretus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lacks detailed collecting information. It may have been collected during the 1905–1906 California Academy of Sciences expedition to the Galápagos Islands and then possibly exchanged or gifted to the USNM. The 
<date id="B64E106331581E36F923C954E5D8839F" box="[322,420,380,401]" pageId="12" value="1906-07">July 1906</date>
material collected by F. X. Williams is mentioned in Van Dyke’ s (1953) overview of the 
<taxonomicName id="05F04D2031581E36F92AC999E5C083C8" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[331,444,433,454]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
of the Galápagos Islands, but 
<collectingCountry id="BAE7763331581E36F97FC9E4E58483EF" box="[286,504,460,481]" name="San Cristobal Island" pageId="12">San Cristóbal Island</collectingCountry>
is not mentioned as among the localities for the 18 dynastine specimens collected by Williams. Since no other specimens have been found in the intervening 108 years, it could be surmised that 
<taxonomicName id="05F04D2031581E36F990CA1EE6028045" authorityName="Ratcliffe" authorityYear="2014" box="[497,638,566,587]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Adelaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretus">
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36F990CA1EE6028045" box="[497,638,566,587]" italics="true" pageId="12">A. anachoretus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an extremely rare endemic that has not been observed in previous collecting efforts due to a secretive life style, or that it is now extinct due possibly to the introduction of predatory invasive vertebrates. 
<bibRefCitation id="A6614B5231581E36F96CCA93E5B580DE" author="Cook" box="[269,457,699,720]" pageId="12" pagination="177 - 193" refId="ref10850" refString="Cook, J., H. F. Howden, and S. B. Peck. 1995. The Galapagos Islands' genus Neoryctes Arrow (Coleoptera: Scarabaeidae: Dynastinae). The Canadian Entomologist 127: 177 - 193." type="journal article" year="1995">
Cook 
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36F92DCA93E50680DE" box="[332,378,699,720]" italics="true" pageId="12">et al</emphasis>
. (1995)
</bibRefCitation>
observed that the then-known four 
<taxonomicName id="05F04D2031581E36F959CAFEE5A080E4" box="[312,476,725,747]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Neoryctes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36F959CAFEE5EF80E5" box="[312,403,726,747]" italics="true" pageId="12">Neoryctes</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in the Galápagos Islands were all rare, due possibly to the inaccessibility of the high elevation habitat, short period of adult nocturnal activity that coincided with rain, or predation by introduced rats, pigs, and ants.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C24F36A331581E36F8CECB72E51A842C" blockId="12.[151,639,194,1570]" pageId="12">
The volcanic islands of the 
<collectingRegion id="0034F84131581E36F9C9CB72E6748161" box="[424,520,858,879]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="12">Galápagos</collectingRegion>
Archipelago are approximately 
<quantity id="05089B4631581E36F928CB5DE5AE8184" box="[329,466,884,906]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" metricValueMax="10.0" metricValueMin="8.0" pageId="12" unit="km" value="900.0" valueMax="1000.0" valueMin="800.0">800–1,000 km</quantity>
west of mainland 
<collectingCountry id="BAE7763331581E36F8F6CBA7E49581AA" box="[151,233,911,932]" name="Ecuador" pageId="12">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. All of the islands are volcanic in origin and semiarid with the lowlands having a short wet season, while the highlands catch fog and rain clouds and are moister (
<bibRefCitation id="A6614B5231581E36F9F9CBF7E63E81FA" author="Van Dyke" box="[408,578,991,1012]" pageId="12" pagination="1 - 181" refId="ref11854" refString="Van Dyke, E. C. 1953. The Coleoptera of the Galapagos Islands. Occasional Papers of the California Academy of Sciences 22: 1 - 181." type="journal article" year="1953">Van Dyke 1953</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation id="A6614B5231581E36FA38CBF7E56C8601" author="Tye" pageId="12" pagination="12 - 23" refId="ref11784" refString="Tye, A, H. L. Snell, S. B. Peck, and H. Andersen. 2002. Outstanding terrestrial features of the Galapagos archipelago [pp. 12 - 23]. In: A Biodiversity Vision for the Galapagos Islands (R. Bensted-Smith, editor). Charles Darwin Foundation and World Wildlife Fund, Puerto Ayora, Galapagos, Ecuador." type="book chapter" year="2002">
Tye 
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36F8F6CBD2E4B88601" box="[151,196,1018,1039]" italics="true" pageId="12">et al</emphasis>
. (2002)
</bibRefCitation>
observed that isolation of the islands has led to a high degree of endemism for vertebrates, and 
<bibRefCitation id="A6614B5231581E36F96BCC07E5FC864A" author="Peck" box="[266,384,1071,1092]" pageId="12" refId="ref11333" refString="Peck, S. B. 2005. The Beetles of the Galapagos Islands, Ecuador; Evolution, Ecology, and Diversity (Insecta: Coleoptera). NRC Research Press, Ottawa, Canada." type="book" year="2005">Peck (2005)</bibRefCitation>
suggested that limitations for establishment of colonizing beetles is more related to the strongly seasonal, semiarid climate of the large, lowland areas of the islands and the prevalence of large areas of young and unweathered lava substrates that are not conducive to beetles. 
<bibRefCitation id="A6614B5231581E36F8F6CCE6E56486ED" author="Peck" box="[151,280,1230,1251]" pageId="12" refId="ref11333" refString="Peck, S. B. 2005. The Beetles of the Galapagos Islands, Ecuador; Evolution, Ecology, and Diversity (Insecta: Coleoptera). NRC Research Press, Ottawa, Canada." type="book" year="2005">Peck (2005)</bibRefCitation>
recorded the beetle fauna of the 
<collectingRegion id="0034F84131581E36F8F6CCC1E53886F0" box="[151,324,1257,1278]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="12">Galápagos Islands</collectingRegion>
at 56 families, 297 genera, and 486 species with 266 endemic species, 110 indigenous species, and 110 introduced species. Previously, 
<taxonomicName id="05F04D2031581E36F888CD11E5388740" authorityName="Arrow" authorityYear="1908" box="[233,324,1337,1358]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Neoryctes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36F888CD11E5388740" box="[233,324,1337,1358]" italics="true" pageId="12">Neoryctes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was the only endemic genus of scarabs in the 
<collectingRegion id="0034F84131581E36F943CD7BE5B28766" box="[290,462,1363,1384]" country="Ecuador" name="Galapagos" pageId="12">Galápagos Islands</collectingRegion>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="A6614B5231581E36F9BBCD7BE6308766" author="Peck" box="[474,588,1363,1384]" pageId="12" refId="ref11333" refString="Peck, S. B. 2005. The Beetles of the Galapagos Islands, Ecuador; Evolution, Ecology, and Diversity (Insecta: Coleoptera). NRC Research Press, Ottawa, Canada." type="book" year="2005">Peck (2005)</bibRefCitation>
concluded that generic endemism and species diversification is strongly correlated with secondary loss of flight wings after colonization, and that most colonization has not been followed by much speciation. Both 
<taxonomicName id="05F04D2031581E36F92ACDF0E59987E3" authorityName="Ratcliffe" authorityYear="2014" box="[331,485,1496,1517]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Adelaeus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="anachoretus">
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36F92ACDF0E59987E3" box="[331,485,1496,1517]" italics="true" pageId="12">A. anachoretus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="05F04D2031581E36FA40CDF0E60287E3" box="[545,638,1496,1517]" class="Insecta" family="Dynastidae" genus="Neoryctes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="12" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="linelli">
<emphasis id="F084EAB131581E36FA40CDF0E60287E3" box="[545,638,1496,1517]" italics="true" pageId="12">N. linelli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
inhabit 
<collectingCountry id="BAE7763331581E36F886CDDAE50C8409" box="[231,368,1522,1543]" name="Saint Kitts and Nevis" pageId="12">San Cristóbal</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="5ACB2A2631581E36F9E5CDDAE5AE8409" box="[388,466,1522,1543]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="11.[197,229,895,914]" captionTargetBox="[173,1193,192,872]" captionTargetId="figure-384@11.[172,1193,192,872]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Fig. 20. El Junco area on Isla San Cristóbal, Galápagos Islands, possible habitat for Adelaeus anachoretus. Photograph courtesy of K. Thalia Grant (Isla Santa Cruz, Galapágos Islands)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5369390" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5369390/files/figure.png" pageId="12">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
), and both have reduced hind wings.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
